V{{Infobox person\u000a|name        = Margaret Anne Ganley Somerville\u000a|image       = \u000a|alt         = \u000a|caption     = \u000a|birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1942|04|13}}\u000a|birth_place = [[Adelaide]], [[South Australia]]\u000a|death_date  = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\u000a|death_place = \u000a|other_names = \u000a|known_for   = \u000a|occupation  = Ethicist\u000a|nationality = \u000a}}\u000a'''Margaret Anne Ganley Somerville''', [[Order of Australia|AM]], [[Royal Society of Canada|FRSC]] (born April 13, 1942) is the Samuel Gale Professor of Law at [[McGill University]], as well as professor in the university's [[McGill University Faculty of Medicine|faculty of medicine]] and the founding director of the [[McGill University Faculty of Law|law faculty]]'s Centre for Medicine, Ethics and Law.\u000a\u000aSomerville was born in [[Adelaide]], South Australia, and educated at [[Mercedes College (Adelaide)|Mercedes College]] ([[Springfield, South Australia|Springfield]], [[South Australia]]). She received a A.u.A. (pharm.) from the [[University of Adelaide]] in 1963, a [[Bachelor of Law]] degree (Hons. I) and the University Medal from the [[University of Sydney]] in 1973, and a D.C.L. from McGill University in 1978.\u000a\u000aIn 1978 she was appointed assistant professor in the law faculty at McGill. She was appointed an associate professor in 1979 and an associate professor in the faculty of medicine in 1980. In 1984 she became a full professor in both faculties, and in 1989 was appointed the Samuel Gale Professor of Law. From 1986 to 1996, she was the founding director of the McGill Centre for Medicine, Ethics and Law and was appointed acting director in 1999. She currently teaches seminars on advanced torts and comparative medical law at McGill.\u000a\u000aIn November 2006 she gave the five annual [[Massey Lectures]] on [[CBC Radio]] in Canada. An expanded version of the lectures was published in Canada, Australia and the United States in book form as ''The Ethical Imagination: Journeys of the Human Spirit''.\u000a\u000a==Honours==\u000aAmong many honours and awards, in 1990, Somerville was made a Member of the [[Order of Australia]] "for service to the law and to bioethics".<ref>[http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=882353&search_type=quick&showInd=true]</ref> In 1991 she was made a Fellow of the [[Royal Society of Canada]]. In 2004 she was chosen by an international jury as the first recipient of [[UNESCO]]'s Avicenna Prize for Ethics in Science.<ref>[http://portal.unesco.org/en/ev.php-URL_ID=20029&URL_DO=DO_TOPIC&URL_SECTION=201.html]</ref>\u000a\u000aShe has received honorary degrees from [[University of Windsor]] (1992), [[Macquarie University]] (1993), [[St. Francis Xavier University]] (1996) and the [[University of Waterloo]] (2004). Her honorary degree awarded June 19, 2006 at [[Ryerson University]] in [[Toronto]] was controversial<ref>http://www.ccrl.ca/index.php?id=331</ref> because of her objections to [[same sex marriage]]. She has since received honorary degrees from [[Mount Saint Vincent University]] in [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]], [[Nova Scotia]] (2009), [[St. Mark's College, Vancouver|St. Mark's College]], [[Vancouver]] (2010) and the [[Royal Military College of Canada]] in [[Kingston, Ontario|Kingston]], [[Ontario]] (2013).\u000a\u000aIn 2006 Somerville was nominated for membership in the [[Order of Canada]] by [[Carol Finlay]], a professor at the [[Toronto School of Theology]]. Finlay says Somerville was turned down for the honour because she was "too controversial."<ref>Aubin, Henry. (2006). ''[http://www.canada.com/montrealgazette/features/viewpoints/story.html?id=62cda378-0d93-4a8b-8d88-010af82ffe62 McGill ethicist refused OC because she was 'too controversial']'', The Montreal Gazette, 8 July 2008.</ref>\u000a\u000a==Involvement in same-sex marriage debate==\u000aSomerville presented both a brief and an oral presentation to the [[Canadian House of Commons Standing Committee on Justice and Human Rights]] opposing the legalization of same-sex marriage in Canada in 2003.<ref>Margaret Somerville [http://www.catholiceducation.org/articles/homosexuality/ho0063.html The Case Against "Same-sex marriage"] Catholic Education Resource Center. Retrieved November 25, 2013</ref> <ref>[http://www.parl.gc.ca/HousePublications/Publication.aspx?Pub=CommitteeMeetingEvidence&Acronym=just&Mee=39&Language=e&Mode=1&Parl=37&Ses=2 37th PARLIAMENT, 2nd SESSION Standing Committee on Justice and Human Rights] Parliament of Canada. Retrieved November 25, 2013</ref>\u000a\u000a==Selected bibliography==\u000a\u000a* ''The Ethical Canary: Science, Society, and the Human Spirit'' (2000, ISBN 0-670-89302-1)\u000a* ''Death Talk: The Case Against Euthanasia and Physician-Assisted Suicide'' (2001, ISBN 0-7735-2201-8)\u000a* ''The Ethical Imagination: Journeys of the Human Spirit'' (2006, ISBN 0-88784-747-1)\u000a* '' Do We Care? '' (May 26, 1999) ISBN 0-7735-1878-9\u000a\u000a==See also==\u000a* [[Avicenna Prize]]\u000a\u000a==Footnotes==\u000a{{Reflist}}\u000a\u000a==References==\u000a* {{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/7.30/content/2007/s1935737.htm|title=Professor Somerville discusses the ethics of medical breakthroughs|work=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]|accessdate=May 28, 2007}}\u000a* {{cite web|url=http://www.law.mcgill.ca/faculty/bio_display-en.htm?printBio=36|title=Margaret A. Somerville|work=[[McGill University]]|accessdate=June 15, 2006 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20060613232218/http://www.law.mcgill.ca/faculty/bio_display-en.htm?printBio=36 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = June 13, 2006}}\u000a* {{cite web|url=http://www.utpress.utoronto.ca/cgi-bin/cw2w3.cgi?p=somervil&t=2517&d=5639|title=Canadian Who's Who 1997 entry|work=[[University of Toronto Press]]|accessdate=June 15, 2006}}\u000a* {{cite web|url=http://www.marriageinstitute.ca/images/somerville.pdf|title=The Case Against Same-Sex Marriage: A Brief Submitted to the Standing Committee on Justice and Human Rights|work=|accessdate=April 29, 2003}}\u000a* {{cite web|url=http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/20060619/ryerson_protest_060619/20060619?hub=TopStories|title=Faculty protests award for Montreal ethicist|work=[[CTV News]]|accessdate=June 19, 2006}}\u000a* {{cite web|url=http://www.canada.com/nationalpost/news/issuesideas/story.html?id=b5ccf378-4a0c-41bb-acbf-b2c581a3e365|title=Spineless and rude - Ryerson University shows how not to award an honorary degree|work=[[National Post]]|accessdate=June 19, 2006}}\u000a\u000a{{Authority control}}\u000a\u000a{{DEFAULTSORT:Somerville, Margaret}}\u000a[[Category:1942 births]]\u000a[[Category:Living people]]\u000a[[Category:Australian academics]]\u000a[[Category:Australian women philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:University of Adelaide alumni]]\u000a[[Category:Sydney Law School alumni]]\u000a[[Category:Canadian legal scholars]]\u000a[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Canada]]\u000a[[Category:McGill University alumni]]\u000a[[Category:McGill University faculty]]\u000a[[Category:Members of the Order of Australia]]\u000a[[Category:Ethicists]]\u000a[[Category:20th-century philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:Canadian philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:Canadian women philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:Roman Catholic philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:Australian Roman Catholics]]\u000a[[Category:Canadian Roman Catholics]]\u000a[[Category:McGill University Faculty of Law alumni]]
